Also has 2 factory 8 round magazines with extended base pads (for mag-well use), and 2 Wilson Combat 9 round magazines.  The 9 rounders work, but I carried the 8 rounders, just because I trusted their feeding more.

Only issues I have ever had with the factory mags were when the recoil spring wore out, I had some feeding issues, as one would expect.  The spring that's in it now has about 300 rounds on it, and I'm including 2 new OEM springs.  This uses standard Kimber pro-sized (4" barrel) springs, same as for 45 ACP models.

The condition of the firearm is good.  Completely functional and no rust, but the steel parts do have some holster wear, as Kimber steel finishes are prone to.  The aluminum frame is in good shape with some handling marks, and the barrel and all other functional components are great.

The Trijicon rear tritium sight is on the gun, and there is a fiber optic sight on the front.  I have and will include the Trijicon front sight, and extra fiber optic inserts as well.  There is also an aftermarket mag-well / main spring housing on the gun that was ground down to fit the low profile grips.  The factory plastic main spring housing is also included.  Holsters included are a custom leather IWB by Tucker Gunleather for comfort, a CompTac C-Tac IWB for speed and onehanded reholstering, and a Fobus paddle for range or open carry use.  All high end and cost a combined $230.

Finally, I am including the original box, manual, lock, and stripping tool, plus a spare stripping tool I made from a paperclip.

Kimber no longer makes stuff in .40, but if they did, you're looking at a combined cost of ~$1700 for this setup if purchased new today.  I'm asking for $700 OBO, including the transfer.  Cash only, face-to-face at my FFL in North Loveland.  If you prefer to meet at an FFL of your choosing, that's fine, but you must arrange and pay for the transfer.  Legal Colorado transfer will be required, so don't bother contacting me if you're a felon or illegal alien.  I will give a satisfaction guarantee through your first time at the range, up to 30 days.  If you don't like it, I will refund your full purchase, less $14 for the two transfers.  More pics available on request.

title: For Sale:  Remington 22-250  with Scope in Excellent Condition
postcontent:
Remington 22-250 in excellent condition

 From Petersonshunting.com article  comparing the .223 with the 22-250 for Varmint Hunting:   http://www.petersenshunting.com/gear-accessories/versus/versus-best-coyote-caliber/
The .22-250 carries over 550 ft-lbs of energy at 500 yards, opposed to the .223, which carries only 402 ft-lbs at best. As the late, great, legendary Jack O’Connor taught, speed kills (especially on thin-skinned predators). Where less-than-perfect hits are concerned, more is better.

Known for inherent accuracy and for being mild-mannered to handload, the .22-250 has one other advantage: During these crazy times of frenzied buying and ammo hoarding, it’s much easier to find on store shelves than .223 ammo.

Protest all you want. There’s no denying the facts. The .22-250 shoots flatter, hits harder, and is more accurate than the .223. Factor in those better hits, coupled with more impact authority,  and this cartridge makes more dead predators. Ditch the .223 and opt for the bigger, stronger, superior .22-250 Remington. — Joseph von Benedikt
